{
  "text": "PirB null mice outperform WT on a delayed matchto-place task As a first step in motivating a study of hippocampal synaptic plasticity in mice lacking PirB function (PirB−/−), hippocampal learning and memory were assessed in a delayed-match-to-place task (DMPT) using a modified Barnes dry maze ( Fig. 1a ) [CITATION_1] . Intact LTP at hippocampal synapses, and functional NMDA receptors are thought to be needed for memory encoding during this task [CITATION_2] . Proper execution of DMPT requires mice to form a stable longterm memory of spatial cues used for navigation. At the same time, as the position of an escape hole changes daily, animals have to acquire additional information that is used only for a period of time; this procedural aspect of DMPT is thought to reflect learning flexibility [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
